-- Abil, Allied Technologies, FirstRand, Gijima: South African Stock Preview
-- B y   M i k e   C o h e n   a n d   N i c k y   S m i t h
-- 2010-09-28T06:29:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-28/altech-bioscience-firstrand-gijima-group-south-african-equity-preview.html
The following stocks may rise or
fall in  South Africa . Symbols are in parentheses and prices are
from the last close.  South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index  rose for the
first time in three days, advancing 244.65, or 0.9 percent, to
28,959.42 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  African Bank Investments Ltd.  (ABL SJ): The financial
services company’s African Bank Ltd. unit will issue 1 billion
rand ($142 million) of unsecured bonds. The share added 22
cents, or 0.6 percent, to 35.32 rand.  Allied Technologies Ltd.  (ALT SJ): The electronics and
telecommunications holding company said first-half earnings in
the six months through August fell to 202 million rand, from 284
million rand a year earlier. The shares retreated 20 cents, or
0.4 percent, to 57.70 rand.  AngloGold Ashanti Ltd.  (ANG SJ): Africa’s largest producer
of the metal is concerned about Australia’s proposed carbon tax
in that country, Chief Executive Officer  Mark Cutifani  said in a
conference call today. AngloGold slumped 5.56 rand, or 1.7
percent, to 317.92 rand.  Bioscience Brands Ltd.  (BIO SJ): The health products
company said its net loss narrowed to 6.4 million rand in the
year through June from 14.7 million rand a year earlier. The
stock was unchanged at 1 cent.  Cape Empowerment Ltd.  (CAP SJ): The investment holding
company said it made a 33 million rand profit in the six months
through June, after posting an 8.2 million-rand loss in the
year-earlier period. The shares rose 1 cent, or 5 percent, to 21
cents.  FirstRand Ltd.  (FSR SJ): Plans by South Africa’s second-
biggest financial-services company to merge its Momentum Group
unit with Metropolitan Holdings Ltd. will be voted on by
shareholders. The deal will create the third-largest listed
insurer in South Africa, with an embedded value of about 30
billion rand. The shares gained 39 cents, or 1.9 percent, to
21.01 rand.  Gijima Group Ltd.  (GIJ SJ): The computer-services company
said net income for the year through June advanced to 158.6
million rand from 110.8 million rand a year earlier. The shares
were unchanged at 84 cents.  Interwaste Holdings Ltd. (IWE SJ): The industrial waste-
management group said sales in the six months through June rose
6 percent to 211.7 million rand. Interwaste was unchanged at 70
cents.  Shares or American depositary receipts of the following South
African companies closed as follows:  Anglo American Plc (AAUKY US) was unchanged at $19.98.
AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (AU US) dropped 0.3 percent to $45.12.
BHP Billiton Ltd. (BBL US) fell 0.4 percent to $63.48. DRDGold
Ltd. (DROOY US) gained 0.6 percent to $5.14. Gold Fields Ltd.
(GFI US) retreated 1.3 percent to $14.86. Harmony Gold Mining
Co. (HMY US) slipped almost 1 percent to $11.31. Impala Platinum
Holdings (IMPUY US) dropped 1 percent to $25.60. Sappi Ltd. (SPP
US) added 1.6 percent to $5.22. Sasol Ltd. (SSL US) rose 0.9
percent to $44.06.  To contact the reporters on this story:
